`lifecycle/` implements the three-phase execution of one cage invocation (`prepare` → `run`/`serve` → `teardown`) behind the single `execute(r: &Resolved) -> Result<i32, CageError>` entry point in `mod.rs`. Depending on this subtree gets a caller a sandboxed subprocess run with guaranteed cleanup: prepare mints a rundir and validates billed-mode preconditions, the run phase execs `bwrap` with the resolved binds/env, and teardown always fires afterward regardless of run outcome, with only prepare/run errors propagating to the caller.

The phases share a `Prep` struct (rundir, rules file, mask file, optional `ClaudeRuntime`) minted in `prepare.rs` and consumed by both the run phase and `teardown_run` — any new resource added to `Prep` needs a corresponding cleanup line in `teardown.rs`, which is scoped to delete only `prep.rundir` and nothing else (ADR-027). Two parallel run implementations exist: `run.rs` (proxy-based, passthrough auth to api.anthropic.com for billed modes) and `serve.rs` (broker-based, brokering only `ctx-access`/`ctx-verify` tool calls) — both wrap `bwrap` execution and both depend on `env.rs`'s bind/PATH resolution and `crate::bwrap`'s `BwrapConfig`/`build_bwrap_args`/socket-path constants, which must stay in sync with whichever run path is active. `env.rs` is pure resolution logic (toolchain dirs, secret masks, PATH assembly, `--clearenv` environment) feeding both `bwrap` bind lists and env construction — its two consumers (bind list, PATH) must be kept consistent or bind visibility and PATH lookup silently diverge.

Cross-cutting invariants: `target_root` is always canonicalized before use (ADR-046, bwrap binds at identical host path); billed modes require a clean git tree unless `allow_dirty`, since the only rollback path is `git` against the pre-run commit; secrets are masked via empty regular files, not `/dev/null` (bind mounts carry `nodev`); `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` is never injected into cage env, since claude's own auth (subscription credential bind or passthrough proxy) handles it and setting the var triggers an interactive prompt that breaks headless runs; teardown never affects the exit code or panics.

